'''D. Graham Burnett''' is an American historian of science and a writer. He is a professor at [[Princeton University]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.princeton.edu/history/people/display_person.xml?netid=dburnett |title= Princeton University History Department |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 6 September 2012 |website= Princeton University History Department |publisher=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |accessdate= 31 March 2014}}</ref> and an editor at ''[[Cabinet magazine|Cabinet]]'', based in Brooklyn, New York. Burnett received his A.B. in [[history]] (concentration in the [[history of science]]) at [[Princeton University]] and an M.Phil and Ph.D. in the history and philosophy of science at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].
Burnett is a member of the Esthetical Society for Transcendental and Applied Realization (now incorporating the Society for Esthetic Realizers) (ESTAR(SER)), a research collective dedicated to studying the historicity of the Order of the Third Bird.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.estarser.net/communiques/?page_id=199|title=ESTAR(SER) {{!}} Communiqués from ESTAR (SER)|website=www.estarser.net|access-date=2016-10-26}}</ref>
