{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use British English|date=October 2016}} '''Katrina Honeyman''' (18 June 1950 &ndash; 23 October 2011) was a British economic historian and Professor of Social and Economic History at the [[University of Leeds]].<ref name="leeds-obit">{{cite web|url=http://www.leeds.ac.uk/secretariat/obituaries/2011/honeyman_katrina.html|title=Professor Katrina Honeyman, BA, PhD, FRHistS, AcSS|last=Cookson|first=Gill|year=2011|work=Obituaries 2011|publisher=University of Leeds|accessdate=12 May 2013}}</ref><ref name="teleg-obit">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/8988576/Professor-Katrina-Honeyman.html|title=Obituaries: Professor Katrina Honeyman|date=2 January 2012|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=12 May 2013}}</ref><ref name="guard-obit">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/nov/02/katrina-honeyman-obituary|title=Katrina Honeyman obituary: Historian who focused on women and children in industry|last=Cookson|first=Gill|date=2 November 2011|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 May 2013}}</ref> Much of her work focused on the role of women and children in industrialisation in Britain.
==Early life== Honeyman was born in London, one of the five children of John and Eleanor Honeyman, and the family later moved to Manchester. She graduated in Economic History and Sociology at the [[University of York]] and then gained a Ph.D. at the [[University of Nottingham]]: her thesis work on the social background of early entrepreneurs was later published as ''Origins of Enterprise''.<ref name=teleg-obit />
==Academic career== Honeyman held temporary posts at the universities of [[University of Aberdeen|Aberdeen]] and [[University of Manchester|Manchester]] before taking up an appointment in the School of Economic and Social Studies at the [[University of Leeds]] in 1979. She worked at Leeds until her death. She was director of the Centre for Business History at Leeds 1993-1997, and in 1997 she moved to the university's School of History, being appointed Professor of Social and Economic History in 2008.<ref name=teleg-obit />
She was President of the [[Association of Business Historians]] for a year, served twice on the council of the [[Economic History Society]], and was editor of the journal ''[[Textile History]]''.<ref name=guard-obit /> She was a Fellow of the [[Royal Historical Society]].<ref name=leeds-obit />
==Selected publications== *''Origins of Enterprise: Business Leadership in the Industrial Revolution'' (1982, [[Manchester University Press|Manchester UP]], {{ISBN|0719008735}}), based on her Ph.D. thesis * ''Technology and Enterprise: Isaac Holden and the Mechanisation of Woolcombing in France, 1848-1914'' (1986, by Katrina Honeyman and Jordan Goodman, Scolar, {{ISBN|0859677273}}) * ''Gainful Pursuits: The Making of Industrial Europe, 1600-1914'' 1988, by Jordan Goodman and Katrina Honeyman, [[Edward Arnold (publisher)|Edward Arnold]], {{ISBN|0713166061}}) * ''Leeds City Business 1893-1993: Essays marking the centenary of the incorporation'' (1993, edited by John Chartres and Katrina Honeyman, University of Leeds Press, {{ISBN|0853161577}}) commemorating the centenary of the [[City status in the United Kingdom|city status]] of Leeds *''Women, Gender and Industrialisation, 1700-1870'' (2000, [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]], {{ISBN|033369077X}}) *''Well Suited: a History of the Leeds Clothing Industry, 1850-1990'' (2000, [[Oxford University Press|Oxford UP]],{{ISBN|0199202370}}) * ''Child Workers in England, 1780-1820: Parish Apprentices and the Making of the Early Industrial Labour Force'' (2007, [[Ashgate Publishing|Ashgate]], {{ISBN|9780754662723}})
